🕵️ Drift-Debugger

Catch and fix hidden numerical drift in ML training.

⸻

❓ Why this exists

You fixed the seed.
You used Docker.
You ran the same code.

And still:

“Why is my loss different on another GPU?”

Most tools (W&B, MLflow) tell you what changed.
drift-debugger tells you:

what invisible system states caused the divergence — and forces them back into alignment.

⸻

🔴 What causes drift?

Even with identical code and seeds, results can diverge due to:
	•	TF32 / FP16 precision differences
	•	cuDNN non-deterministic kernels
	•	GPU architecture (A100 vs 4090)
	•	Hidden backend flags (torch.backends.*)
	•	CUDA / driver mismatches

⸻

🚀 Quick Start

pip install drift-debugger

1️⃣ Capture environment fingerprint

drift run python train.py

→ generates drift_fingerprint.json

⸻

2️⃣ Find divergence

drift diff runA.json runB.json

Example output:

⚠️ Divergence detected
- tf32_allowed: True vs False
- cudnn_deterministic: False vs True


⸻

3️⃣ Fix it (the key feature)

drift patch runA.json

This generates:

drift_patch.py

Then in your training script:

import drift_patch

✅ Your environment is now bitwise-aligned with the baseline.

